Chapter 1: The Scavenger’s Burden
The Scene: The "Epsilon-4" Gate. It’s a Rank D dungeon that was cleared two hours ago by the Iron Vanguard Guild. Now, it’s the Scavengers' turn to do the dirty work.
Part 1: The Weight of the World
The air inside the Gate tasted like wet copper and ozone. Leon wiped a bead of sweat from his forehead, his knuckles white as he gripped the handle of his rusted extraction hook.
"Hey, Trash-tier! Move it!"
A heavy boot slammed into Leon’s shoulder, sending him stumbling into the carcass of a Gravelight Boar. Leon didn't look up. He knew that voice. It was Chadric, a C-Rank Squire from the academy—someone who enjoyed the "perks" of his rank a bit too much.
"Sorry," Leon muttered, his voice flat. He kept his eyes on the boar, carefully peeling back the hide to find any scrap of usable leather the Slayers had missed.
[Current Status: Leon (Rank F)]
[Class: Scavenger]
[Stamina: 14/40]
[Mana: 0/0]
The blue screen hovered mockingly in his peripheral vision. To anyone else, it was a symbol of potential. To Leon, it was a cage. He had no mana, no combat skills, and a stamina bar that depleted just from dragging a cart.
Part 2: The Motivation
His phone vibrated in his pocket. He took a risk, pulling it out while Chadric was busy laughing with his friends further down the tunnel. It was a text from the automated home-monitor.
> ALERT: Patient 'Liora' - Mana-Lag Saturation: 74%. Immediate infusion of High-Grade Essence recommended.
> 
Leon’s heart skipped. 74%. Last week it was 68%. The medical bills were piling up, and the "trash" he was collecting today would barely cover the rent, let alone a Mana-Crystal.
"I need something bigger," Leon whispered to himself, looking toward the deeper, darker tunnels of the Gate—the areas the Slayers usually ignored because the monsters were "too small" to be worth their time.
Part 3: The Danger
Suddenly, the ground shivered. Not a tremor, but a ripple, like the world was made of liquid.
The blue System screens of the Slayers nearby began to flicker. Leon’s own screen didn't just flicker—it screamed. A high-pitched digital whine echoed in his skull, and the blue light bled into a violent, jagged red.
[SYSTEM WARNING: GATE STABILITY CRITICAL]
[DETECTION ERROR: Unknown Entity Re-manifesting...]
[LOGIC BREACH IN PROGRESS]
"What the hell is happening?" Chadric yelled, his sword glowing with a faint, trembling light. "The Gate was cleared!"
From the shadows of the "cleared" tunnel, a pair of glowing, glitching eyes opened. It wasn't a monster from the Bestiary. It looked like a wolf made of static and broken code.

This is a smart way to maintain tension. If Leon becomes a god in Chapter 1, the story loses its stakes. By keeping his growth "fast but earned" and his power a secret, we create a Double Life dynamic: Leon the "F-Rank Trash" by day, and the "System Glitch" by night.
Let's go with Path 3: The Awakening, but we’ll make it a desperate, messy survival rather than a clean victory.
Chapter 1: The Scavenger’s Burden (Continued)
The static-wolf—a [Glitched Void-Stalker]—didn't move like a biological creature. It stuttered through the air, its limbs snapping from one position to another like a lagging video feed.
"Run! It’s a Gate-Collapse!" Chadric screamed, his C-Rank bravado vanishing. He didn't even try to swing his glowing sword; he just turned and bolted toward the extraction point, leaving Leon and the other scavengers behind.
Leon didn't run. He couldn't. His [Stamina: 4/40] was flashing red. His legs felt like lead.
The wolf lunged.
Leon raised his rusted scavenging hook—a tool meant for dragging carcasses, not killing them—in a pathetic defensive arc. As the wolf’s static-filled maw closed in, Leon’s vision didn't fade to black. It exploded into Red Error Code.
> [LOGIC CONFLICT DETECTED]
> [ENTITY: VOID-STALKER (LEVEL 25) vs. ENTITY: LEON (LEVEL 1)]
> [RESULT: IMPOSSIBLE ENCOUNTER]
> [INITIATING SYSTEM WORKAROUND...]
> 
Time slowed. A red box appeared over the wolf’s throat, flickering with the words [NULL POINTER].
Leon didn't think. He swung the hook. Usually, the rusted metal would have snapped against a Level 25 hide. But as the hook passed through the red box, the metal glitched. For a microsecond, the hook wasn't metal—it was a jagged line of raw, corrupted data.
SHRED.
The wolf didn't bleed. It pixelated. A chunk of its neck simply ceased to exist. The creature let out a sound like a distorted radio frequency and collapsed, its body dissolving into black cubes.
> [ERROR: UNAUTHORIZED KILL DETECTED]
> [EXPERIENCE CALCULATION FAILED]
> [CONVERTING KILL-DATA TO FRAGMENTS...]
> [RECEIVED: 1x 'VOID FRAGMENT' (CORRUPTED)]
> 
Leon gasped for air, his heart hammering against his ribs. He was alive. But he wasn't "leveled up." He felt just as weak as before, his muscles aching and his lungs burning.
He looked at his hook. The rusted tip was now permanently stained with a faint, pulsing violet static.
"Leon? Did... did you kill that thing?"
One of the other scavengers, an old man named Havi, stared from behind a rock.
Leon quickly shoved the hook into his leather sheath, hiding the violet glow. If the Guild found out a Scavenger had killed a Level 25 monster with a rusted tool, they’d haul him to a laboratory by morning.
"No," Leon lied, his voice shaking. "It... it just dissolved. The Gate-Collapse must have de-spawned it. We need to go. Now."
The "Fast but Earned" Growth Plan
To keep him from becoming OP too quickly, we will use the Fragment System:
 * No Free Levels: Leon doesn't get "Stat Points" for kills. He has to manually use [Data Fragments] to "Patch" his own body or his gear.
 * The Cost: Patching his body is painful and slow. If he does it too fast, his "Human Code" might break.
 * The Disguise: He will spend his first few fragments on a skill called [False Mask], which makes his Status Window look like a normal, weak F-Rank Scavenger to anyone who inspects him.
